		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Lorelei's Roleplaying Guide</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:lorelei38@hotmail.com">lorelei38</a> | 
		            3/6/2000 5:38:26 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Welcome!<BR>
<BR>
So, you want to roleplay, do ya? Good. Roleplaying is sorta like acting. You take on a new personality and act like that person. EverQuest was meant to be a roleplaying game, but the sad truth is it is not now.<BR>
Let me tell you, if you roleplay you will be in the minority. It's hard to find other people to roleplay along with you, most people will just give you weird stares and/or insult you. Ignore them. You're playing the game your way, they are theirs.<BR>
Now, you have to decide what character to roleplay. Some are easy to choose a personality for, like a Paladin or Necromancer, but some are kinda tricky, like an Enchanter or Mage. Whatever you choose, it's up to YOU to create his/her personality. It's also a good idea to try and make up a history of the character. Things like his/her parent's names, basic family history, childhood. You don't need to go into great detail, not many do.<BR>
Now that you have your character, and the past is set up, build on it. Use events from the character's past to determine what he/she should say, act like, be like. For example I play a Mage normally hard to roleplay, but because of events in her past, mostly the death of her parents, she has become a loner and dosen't really like others' company. Things stem from a character's past, and influences what a character is like. You might want to consider writing a diary of your character, in game or no, to help you.<BR>
You are now started down the road. But here are some tips to help you:<BR>
One: Casters like the Mage, Enchanter and Wizard are tricky to roleplay, they don't have any set personality or expectations like a Cleric or Necromancer does. This means you'll have to use your imagination in coming up with a personality for them.<BR>
Two: Don't overuse archaic speech. When most people think of roleplaying they thing of people spouting off bad poetry, overusing thees and thous and making a fool of themselves. Archaic speech is good, but if you overuse it you will sound like an idiot.<BR>
Three: This IS a fantasy land, so do NOT start talking about modern practices, people or devices out of OOC or /tell.<BR>
Four: If you want to powerlevel, I would not suggest roleplaying. Roleplaying is meant to build a person's CHARACTER, not his level.<BR>
<BR>
Good hunting to all!<BR>
<BR>
Lorelei
			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
