	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				I don't mean anything against you Lorelei, but sometimes certain stories get overused. Always try to think of something original. The story of a person disliking people in general or having a particular hatred for a certain race because their father/mother/sister/brother/lover was killed is used quite often, and doesn't really make you stand out. I'm guilty of this one too (I had a magician with a hatred for goblins because his fiancee was ripped apart when goblins raided his camp in Everfrost. He still wears the engagement ring to this day, bla bla bla). It is much more interesting if you can think of something original (such as a dwarven rogue who believes that many races are inferior to BlackBurrow gnolls... &quot;Nobody can outbrew a BlackBurrow. That Stout can knock even a dwarf under the table. Plus, unlike you humans, they had the good sense to build their lair underground. And they really fight tooth and nail. I tell you, with a little motivation they could take over this entire coastline...&quot; &quot;But what about goblins, Dewar?&quot; &quot;Gah, they're just copying dwarven culture. Plus, have you ever tried Goblin Ale? It's about as alcoholic as Elf Water!&quot;). If you can come up with something truly original, people remember you much better... but every once in a while, it does feel good to play that dark-hearted loner, just because it's such a classic character...
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
